---
/**
 * Page transition curtain — a dark panel that sweeps UP over the page
 * on internal navigation (exit), and continues up and away once the
 * next page has loaded (enter). Reads as one continuous wipe; the
 * upward motion + #222 panel match the loader curtain / side-nav
 * language.
 *
 * Wiring lives in scripts/page-transition.ts. The covering arrival
 * state is set synchronously by an inline <head> script in BaseLayout
 * (html[data-pt]) so the new document's first paint is already dark —
 * no flash between pages.
 */
---

<div class="pt" id="page-transition" aria-hidden="true"></div>

<style>
  .pt {
    position: fixed;
    inset: 0;
    /* Above everything — contact panel is 1000, side-nav 900. */
    z-index: 2000;
    background: #222;
    /* Resting: covering but invisible + untouchable. GSAP owns the
       transform (yPercent) during the sweeps — no CSS transform here
       (the translate-vs-yPercent matrix trap). */
    visibility: hidden;
    pointer-events: none;
    will-change: transform;
  }

  /* Arrival — html[data-pt] is set in <head> before first paint.
     IMPORTANT: the cover must NOT depend on the curtain element
     itself — on long documents (the landing) the browser paints
     progressively before the parser reaches this element at the end
     of <body>, which flashed the cream page. So the attribute hides
     the whole body and darkens the root; page-transition.ts makes the
     body visible only once the curtain (inline GSAP state) is
     actually holding the screen. */
  :global(html[data-pt]) {
    background: #222;
  }

  :global(html[data-pt] body) {
    visibility: hidden;
  }

  /* The curtain re-enables its own visibility under the hidden body. */
  :global(html[data-pt]) .pt {
    visibility: visible;
  }
</style>
